Members of the Wales Assembly concerned about "passing as puppets"
Welsh elected representatives are appalled by a proposal to replace their title with the name MWP (Member of the Welsh Parliament, Member of the Welsh Parliament).
This proposal stems from the proposed amendment to the name of the Assembly, which would become the Welsh Parliament.
In the political sphere, members of the Assembly believe that this could be the subject of mockery.
One Labour member said that his group was concerned that the acronym "Rhyme with Twp and Pwp".
For non-Wales readers: in Welsh, twp means stupid, and pwp means crotte.
According to one of its members, the Plaid Cymru (Wales Party) is not "satisfied" and has proposed other formulas.
The Conservative party would be "open" to a name change, but noted that between MWP and Muppet (marionnette), the distance is narrow.
In this context, in Welsh, the letter w is pronounced as the letter u in English from the Yorkshire region.
The Assembly Committee, which is currently preparing legislation introducing the change of name, has indicated that "the final decision on the name of the members of the Assembly is the responsibility of the members of the Assembly".
The Government of Wales Act of 2017 gives the Welsh Assembly the power to change its name.
In June, the Commission published the results of a public consultation on the proposal to designate the Assembly as a Welsh Parliament, which was widely supported.
On the question of the title of members, the Commission favours Members of the Welsh Parliament (or WMP); however, a large majority of Welsh preferred MWP.
It seems that the members of the Assembly are making other suggestions, but the effort to reach consensus could prove to be a real puzzle for Elin Jones, the Speaker of the Assembly, who is expected to submit a name change bill in the coming weeks.
The reform legislation will include other changes concerning the functioning of the assembly, including rules on the exclusion of members and the design of the committee system.
Members of the Assembly will take the final decision on the name issue during the debate on the bill.
