"I came today to vote for the future of my country, for the youth of Macedonia, so that it can live freely under the aegis of the European Union, which means a safer life for all of us," said Olivera Georgijevska, 79, in Skopje.
Although the vote is not legally binding, enough members of parliament have said that they will follow the result of the vote to make it decisive.
The change of name would require a two-thirds majority in parliament.
The State Election Commission announced that no irregularities had been detected at 1 p.m.
But the turnout was only 16%, compared to 34% at the same time in the last parliamentary elections in 2016, which mobilized 66% of the registered voters after the vote.
"I came to vote for my children. Our place is in Europe," says Gjose Tanevski, 62, who voted in the capital, Skopje.
Macedonian Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and his son Dushko participated in the referendum and voted for the change of name, in order to open the vote for membership of NATO and the European Union, in Strumica, Macedonia, on 30 September 2018.
