"We want to enter the EU and NATO, but we want to enter through the big door," said Kavadarkov.
"We are a poor country, but we have our dignity.
If they do not want us as Macedonia, we can turn to China and Russia and participate in Eurasian integration."
According to Prime Minister Zaev, NATO membership will allow Macedonia to benefit from the necessary investments. The unemployment rate in the country exceeds 20%.
"I think a large majority will be in favour, because more than 80% of our citizens want to join the EU and NATO," said Mr Zaev after tabling his ballot.
He added that a "yes" would be a "confirmation of our future."
According to a poll published on Monday by the Institute for Policy Research of Macedonia, between 30 and 43 per cent of voters intend to participate in the referendum, which is below the expected turnout.
Another survey, organized by the Macedonian channel Telma, estimated the participation at 57 per cent.
70% of participants intending to vote said they would vote "yes."
