On the importance of a responsible economic policy, on national security, on Europe. Ironically, these are issues on which Jeremy himself disagreed with previous leaders.
The notification for the Nottingham East Labour rally on Friday said, "We want the rally to be inclusive and productive."
This is exactly what the Friday night general assemblies were like during my eight years as a Labour Party parliamentarian.
Unfortunately, today there are not many gatherings and the promise of softer and more respectful policies has been forgotten for a long time, if it has ever been taken into consideration.
It has become clear that contrary opinions are no longer tolerated within the party. Each opinion is judged according to its acceptability by the party leaders.
It started shortly after Jeremy took power, and the colleagues with whom I thought I shared the same political vision began to expect me to turn over my jacket and take positions that were contrary to my convictions, whether it was about national security or the EU internal market.
Every time I spoke publicly, and no matter what I said, followed an abusive tirade on social networks, calling for withdrawal, denouncing the policies of the center, telling me that I should not be a member of the party.
And it's not just my experience.
Moreover, I am more fortunate than some of my colleagues, because the comments addressed to me were of a political nature.
I am in admiration for the professionalism and determination of these colleagues, who are confronted with sexist or racist statements every day, but who do not give up.
One of the most disappointing things in current policy is the normalization of different forms of abuse.
Last week, Jeremy Corbyn said the Labour Party should encourage a culture of tolerance.
The reality is that we are no longer this large community and that the party is narrowing down through the motions of disbelief and changes to the rules of selection.
I've been given a lot of advice over the past two years: look down, not express my ideas so loud, and everything would be fine.
But it is not to act like this that I do politics.
I joined the Labour Party 32 years ago as a schoolboy, because the negligence of Thatcher's government had caused my classroom to collapse. Since then, I have wanted to work for better public services for those who need it most, whether as a local councillor or government minister.
I have never hidden my political ambitions, even in the last elections.
No one in Nottingham East could be disturbed by my political positions and my differences with the current party leaders.
All I would like to say to those who defended the motion on Friday is that the country is moving towards a Brexit that will affect homes, businesses and public services. I think this is not really the time to waste time and energy debating my loyalty to the party leader.
My only message is not for Nottingham Momentum, it is for my constituents, whether they are Labour or not: I am proud to serve you and I promise you that no threat of withdrawal or opportunism will prevent me from acting for the causes I defend, which are your common interests.
