“The sea is ours”: Bolivia, blocked, hopes that the court will reopen the way to the Pacific
Sailors patrol an armoured boat at La Paz Naval Headquarters.
Public buildings have a blue flag like the ocean.
From Lake Titicaca to the Amazon, the naval bases display the following motorcycle: "The sea is ours.
Recovering it is a duty."
Throughout blocked Bolivia, the memory of a coast lost to Chile during a conflict of blood resources in the nineteenth century is still present. Just as the desire to sail over the Pacific Ocean, once again.
These hopes have not been so palpable for several decades: Bolivia is indeed awaiting a decision by the International Court of Justice, which will be delivered on 1 October, after five years of deliberations.
"Bolivia has the will, a spirit of unity and serenity, and of course expects a positive result," explains Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will follow the ruling of the International Court of Justice on a large screen throughout the country, hoping that the Hague Court will decide in favour of Bolivia's request. Bolivia hopes that, after decades of sporadic negotiations, Chile will be obliged to negotiate the agreement of a sovereign passage to the ocean to Bolivia.
Evo Morales, the charismatic indigenous president of Bolivia (who is facing a controversial fight for the re-election next year), also has a lot to say about the decision to be rendered on Monday.
"We are so close to returning to the Pacific Ocean," he said at the end of August.
But some analysts believe that there is little chance that the court will rule in favour of Chile, and that little would change, even in the event of a positive decision.
The United Nations body based in the Netherlands does not have the power to grant Chilean territory, and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of any talks.
The fact that the International Court of Justice renders its decision six months after the last arguments shows that the case “was not complicated”, explains Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert in international law.
And far from promoting the cause of Bolivia, the past four years have perhaps even harmed it.
"The problem of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian administration," said Zárate.
Morales' belligerent rhetoric undermined all the Chilean goodwill that remained, she suggested.
Bolivia and Chile will continue to exchange views, but after that it will be very difficult to hold talks.
The last exchange of ambassadors between the two countries took place in 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, who represents Bolivia in the Hague, rejected the idea that the Court's decision-making was abnormally rapid.
Monday will bring Bolivia "an extraordinary opportunity to start a new era of relations with Chile" and a chance to "end 139 years of disagreements with mutual benefits," he said.
Calzadilla also challenged the fact that Morales - who so far remains one of the most popular presidents in Latin America - used the maritime problem as a political crutches.
"Bolivia will never give up its right of access to the Pacific Ocean," he added.
"The Court's decision is an opportunity to see that we must get rid of the past."
