North Korea declares that disarmament can in no way be achieved unilaterally without confidence.
On Saturday, the North Korean Foreign Minister told the United Nations that the maintenance of sanctions reinforced his distrust of the United States and that it would be impossible for his country to unilaterally renounce its nuclear weapons under these circumstances.
At the annual General Assembly of the global organization, Ri Yong Ho stated that North Korea had taken “important measures of goodwill” last year, such as putting an end to such things as the cessation of nuclear testing and missiles, the dismantling of the nuclear test site and its commitment not to proliferate nuclear weapons and technology.
"However, we see no corresponding response from the United States," he regretted.
In the absence of confidence in the United States, we will fear for our national security and, in such circumstances, we cannot be the first to disarm unilaterally."
While reiterating North Korea's well-known criticism of Washington's opposition to a "step-by-step" approach to denuclearization under which North Korea would be rewarded if it took steps gradually, its statement proved important in that it did not reject the idea of unilateral denuclearization as Pyongyang had done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump, made on 12 June in Singapore at the very first summit between an incumbent US president and a North Korean leader, when Kim pledged to work for a "denuclearization of the Korean peninsula" while Trump promised to guarantee North Korea's security.
North Korea seeks to officially end the Korean War (1950-1953), but the United States has stated that Pyongyang must first renounce its nuclear weapons.
Washington also refused requests to relax severe international sanctions against North Korea.
the United States insists that North Korea first proceed to denuclearization and increase the pressure by imposing sanctions to achieve their objective in a coercive way, even opposing the "declaration of an end to war"."
"Those who think these sanctions can make us bend don't know us.
The problem is that the maintenance of sanctions increases our mistrust."
Ri made no comments on the second summit between Kim and Trump, which the US leader highlighted in front of the UN earlier this week.
Instead, the Minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: "If the party concerned by the issue of denuclearization were South Korea and not the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not be in such an impasse."
Despite this, Ri's tone of speech was radically different from last year's, when he said before the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to point North Korean missiles at North America after President Trump called Kim a "missile man" on a suicide mission.
Trump, who threatened last year before the United Nations to "totally destroy" North Korea, has not paid tribute this year to the courage with which Kim has implemented disarmament measures, but added that much remains to be done and that the sanctions would not be lifted until North Korea disarms.
On Wednesday, Trump said no deadline had been set."It can take two years, three years or five months; it doesn't matter," he said.
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures adopted.
However, US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council last Thursday: "The application of Security Council sanctions must be firmly and systematically maintained until complete, definitive and verified denuclearisation."
The Security Council has unanimously tightened sanctions against North Korea since 2006 in order to stifle the financing of Pyongyang nuclear programmes and ballistic missiles.
Pompeo met Ri on the margins of the UN General Assembly and then announced that he would return to Pyongyang next month to prepare for a second summit.
This year, Pompeo has already travelled to North Korea three times, but his last trip was somewhat disastrous.
In July, he left Pyongyang claiming that progress had been made, but in the hours that followed, North Korea denounced its "gangster methods."
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle a missile site and a nuclear complex if the United States took "equivalent measures".
He has, according to South Korean President Kim, called for the security guarantees Trump promised in Singapore, and for efforts to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard: Students Take Rest Courses
This year, Harvard University introduced a new course that allows all undergraduate students to sleep more and fights against the growing macho trend of studying by consuming caffeine all night long.
One professor noticed that most students at the best university in the world do not know how to take care of them
This course, designed by Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, is, according to him, the first of its kind in the United States.
It was after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning that the idea came to him.
In the end, a student approached me and said, "Why is this only said to me in the last year?"
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
Delivered for the first time this year, this course explains to students the need to adopt good sleep habits to improve their academic and physical performance, as well as their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, Professor of Psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and Director General of Health Services at the University, stated that the University had decided to introduce the course after finding that the students were suffering from a severe lack of sleep during the week.
The course time consists of various interactive exercises.
One of the sections presents the image of a dormitory containing different objects (coffee boxes, curtains, sneakers, books...) on which students click to know the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of lack of sleep on their physical performance and the importance of integrating a routine before bedtime.
In another section, participants learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons then invites participants to reflect on their daily routine.
"We know that this will not instantly change student behaviour.
However, in our view, they have the right to know this information - in the same way that you have the right to know what the health effects of smoking are," added Professor Czeisler.
According to him, the culture of pride in "spending a sleepless night" still exists, and he adds that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students make lack of sleep a growing problem.
Having sufficient and good quality sleep should be the "secret weapon" of the students to fight stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said - even to avoid gaining weight, because lack of sleep puts the brain into mode of inanition, making them permanently hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student in chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design this course after being one of his students last year, during his first year at Harvard.
He stated that the course opened his eyes and urged him to insist that it be offered throughout the campus.
He hoped that the next step would be to offer all postgraduate students a similar program of study before joining the renowned institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students provide an alarm for both the time of bedtime and the time of awakening, and that they be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED light, which can disrupt their circadian rhythm and lead to sleep disturbances.
