Almanach : The inventor of the Geiger meter
And now, a page from our Almanach "Sunday Morning": September 30, 1882, 136 years ago today, and THE ACCOUNTER TOURNE...was born the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger, in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity; an invention that later gave rise to the device known as the Geiger counter.
A pillar of science since then, the Geiger counter has also become fundamental in pop culture, as can be seen in the 1950 film "Bells of Coronado", with Roy Rogers and Dale Evans, two improbable scientists:
A man: "What is this?"
Rogers: "It's a Geiger meter, it's used to look for radioactive minerals, like uranium.
Thanks to these headphones, we can really hear the effects of atoms released into the minerals by radioactivity."
Evans: "Say, it's sure to jump!"
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, a few days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name remains.
A new cancer vaccine allows the immune system to "detect" cancer cells
A new cancer vaccine allows the immune system to "detect" cancer cells and kill them
As part of the treatment, the vaccine tells the immune system how to recognize cancer cells
This technique consists of extracting immune cells from a patient and modifying them in a laboratory
They can then "detect" a protein that is common to many cancers, and are then re-injected
An experimental vaccine shows encouraging results in patients with different types of cancer.
A woman who received the vaccine, whose goal is to teach the immune system to recognize cancer cells, saw her ovarian cancer disappear for more than 18 months.
The method consists in extracting immune cells from a patient and modifying them in the laboratory, so that they can detect the HER2 protein, common to many cancers, and finally re-inject them.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the American National Cancer Institute based in Bethesda, Maryland, said: "Our results indicate that we have a very promising vaccine."
According to Professor Berzofsky, the HER2 protein "produces an increase in several types of cancer", including breast cancer, ovarian cancer, lung cancer and colorectal cancer.
A similar approach, which involves taking immune cells to "learn" them to target cancer cells, has proven successful in the treatment of a type of leukemia.
