What is the Global Citizen Festival and has it done something to reduce poverty?
This Saturday, New York will host the Global Citizen Festival, an annual musical event with a very impressive star list and an equally impressive mission: to end poverty in the world.
The Global Citizen Festival, now in its seventh edition, will see tens of thousands of people rushing to the Great Lawn in Central Park to not only benefit from the performance of artists such as Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Shawn Mendes, but also to raise awareness of the festival's true goal of ending extreme poverty by 2030.
The Global Citizen Festival, first held in 2012, is a Global Poverty Project, an international advocacy group that hopes to eradicate poverty by increasing the number of people actively fighting it.
In order to receive a free ticket to the event (unless you are willing to pay for a VIP ticket), spectators had to perform a series of tasks, or "actions", such as volunteering, e-mail a world leader, phone or make any other useful effort to raise public awareness of the fight against poverty.
But to what extent can the Global Citizen still achieve its goal in the remaining twelve years?
Does the idea of rewarding people with a free concert really persuade them to demand a call for action, or is it just another example of "clickivism" - a situation in which people really think they make a difference by signing a petition or sending a tweet?
Since 2011, Global Citizen has registered more than 19 million "actions" from its supporters, who advocate for many different goals.
According to the organization, these actions have helped drive world leaders to make commitments and adopt policies amounting to more than $37 billion that are expected to change the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
In early 2018, the group mentioned 390 commitments and announcements arising from its shares, of which a tranche of at least $10 billion has already been disbursed or lifted.
