The inventor of the World Wide Web plans to launch a New Internet to challenge Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, is launching a brand new company that seeks to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest technology legend project, Inrupt, is a company that takes advantage of Berners-Lee's Solid Free Platform.
Solid allows users to choose where their data is backed up as well as who is allowed access to such information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that Inrupt aimed to "dominate the world."
"We have to do it now," he said about the launch.
"It's a historic moment."
The application uses Solid's technology to enable people to create their own "online personal data store" or DPL.
It may contain contact lists, task lists, a calendar, a music library and other personal and professional tools.
It is as if Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify were all available at the same time on a single browser.
The particularity of the online personal data store is that it is entirely up to the user to decide who can access what type of information.
The company calls this "personal responsibility via data".
According to the CEO of the company, John Bruce, Inrupt's idea is for the company to provide appropriate resources, processes and skills to make Solid accessible to all.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, a few developers working under contract on the project and a community of volunteer coders.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world will be able to create their own decentralized applications using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee stated that he and his team are not yet in discussion with "Facebook and Google" to find out whether or not to make a complete change where all their business models are completely upset in an instant.
"We don't ask them for permission."
In a Saturday article on Medium, Berners-Lee writes that "the mission [of Inrupt] is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem in order to protect the integrity and quality of the new web built on Solid."
In 1994, at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet by creating the World Wide Web Consortium.
Over the past few months, Berners-Lee has been an influential voice in the debate on network neutrality.
Although he launched Inrupt, Berners-Lee will remain the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
"I am extremely optimistic about this new era of the web," added Berners-Lee.
