Later he rushed to the line of fire and, with the "greatest bravery," guided the line before blowing up a field cannon on his own and knocking down three soldiers from the detachment.
On October 4, 1918, a German sniper killed Lieutenant-Colonel Vann, a little more than a month before the end of the war.
Michael Vann, 72, said that his grandfather's actions were "a thing that I will never be, but that makes me humble."
He and his brother, Dr.James Vann, also laid a wreath after the parade led by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
Michael Vann said he felt "very honoured to be part of the parade" and added that "the courage of an authentic hero is reflected in the support that will be given to him by many people."
