Brexit: The United Kingdom would "forever regret" the departure of car manufacturers.
According to Greg Clark, Secretary of State for Trade, the United Kingdom "would regret it forever" if it lost its status as a world leader in car manufacturing after Brexit.
He added that it was "worrisome" that Toyota UK told the BBC that it would temporarily stop production at its Burnaston plant near Derby if Britain withdrew from the EU without an agreement.
"We need an agreement," said Clark.
The Japanese car manufacturer indicated that the impact of delays at the border in the event of a Brexit without agreement could cost jobs.
The Burnaston plant - which manufactures Toyota's Auris and Avensis vehicles - built nearly 150,000 cars last year, 90% of which were exported to other EU countries.
"I consider that if Britain leaves the EU at the end of March, production will stop at our plant," said Marvin Cooke, Toyota manager in Burnaston.
Other UK car manufacturers, including Honda, BMW and Jaguar Land Rover, have expressed their fear of leaving the EU without agreement on the functioning of cross-border trade.
For example, BMW indicates that it will close its Mini plant in Oxford for a month following Brexit.
The biggest concerns are what car manufacturers call a supply chain risk in the event of Brexit without agreement.
Toyota's production line is operated in "stretched flow", parts arrive every 37 minutes from suppliers from the UK and the EU for custom-made vehicles.
If on 29 March the UK leaves the EU without agreement, there could be disruptions at the border which, according to industry, could lead to delays and shortages of parts.
It would be impossible for Toyota to hold the inventory for more than a day at its Derbyshire plant, said the company, and therefore production would be stopped.
According to Clark, Theresa May's Chequers plan for future relations with the EU is "precisely calibrated to avoid these border controls."
"We need an agreement. We want to have the best agreement that will, as I said, not only take advantage of the current success, but also seize this opportunity," he said on BBC Radio 4's Today.
"The evidence, not only from Toyota but from other manufacturers, is that we absolutely need to be able to maintain what has proven to be an excellent set of supply chains."
While Toyota was unable to specify how long production would be shut down, it cautioned that in the longer term, additional costs would reduce the plant's competitiveness and eventually cost jobs.
Peter Tsouvallaris, the coordinator of the Unite union at the factory and who has worked for 24 years in Burnaston, said that his members were increasingly concerned: "In my experience, once these jobs disappear, they never return."
A government spokesman said: "We have proposed a clear and credible plan for our future relations with the EU."
