Foreign buyers will be subject to a higher stamp duty if they buy a property in the United Kingdom
Foreign buyers will have to pay higher stamp duties if they buy a property in the UK and the extra money will be used to help the homeless under the new conservative regimes.
This measure will reverse Corbyn's successful campaign to attract young voters
The increase in stamp duty will be imposed on those who do not pay tax in the United Kingdom
The Treasury expects to collect up to £120 million Sterling a year to help the homeless.
Foreign buyers will be subject to a higher stamp duty rate if they buy a property in the UK - the extra money will be used to help the homeless, Theresa May will announce today.
This measure will be seen as an initiative to neutralize the success of Jeremy Corbyn's campaign to attract young voters by committing to providing more affordable housing and targeting high-income people.
The increase in the stamp duty will be imposed on individuals and businesses who do not pay taxes in the United Kingdom, and the additional money will be used to strengthen the government's efforts in the fight to help the homeless.
This surtax - in addition to the current stamp duty, including the higher levels introduced two years ago on second homes and purchase-leases - could be as high as 3%.
The Treasury expects the project to raise up to £120 million per year.
About 13 per cent of new London buildings are purchased by non-residents of the United Kingdom, raising prices and preventing first-time entrants from entering the housing market.
Many rich areas of the country - especially in the capital - have become "ghost cities" because of the large number of foreign buyers who stay mostly outside the country.
This new policy comes just a few weeks after Boris Johnson demanded a reduction in stamp duty to help more young people acquire a first home.
Accusing large construction companies to keep housing prices high by grabbing land without using it, he called on May to give up quotas on affordable housing with a view to settling the "real estate disgrace" in the UK.
Mr. Corbyn presented an attractive series of reform proposals in the housing sector, including the monitoring of rents and the elimination of “no-fault” evictions.
It also wishes to give the councils more powers to build new housing.
May said: "Last year, I said that I would dedicate my position as Prime Minister to the rebirth of the British dream - that every new generation would have a better life.
To do this, we need to repair our broken housing market.
Britain will always be open to all those who want to live, work and build a life here.
It is unfair, however, that it is as easy for individuals who do not reside in the United Kingdom, as it is for foreign companies, to buy a home as it is for hard-working British residents.
For too many people, the dream of gaining access to property has become remote and the misery of the homeless remains too real."
